<subSubSection id="0C337F2D6B2FA654C0A230F9EF3D9291" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="71E327953C9B4F1B9112FDB48B16E0A2" pageNumber="32">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="7211DB3218259529A5E1BB214F4B1E4C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CF263E47-E7D3-4AE5-9772-5A3D28FE0624" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis Eigenmann 1912:130, 155" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microglanis</taxonomicName>
was proposed by Eigenmann (1912) to include 
<taxonomicName id="4450DB082F8842D83B7849429B8959D8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E902F0B2-DB73-4580-B19B-675A40A48FDB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis poecilus Eigenmann 1912:155" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="poecilus">Microglanis poecilus</taxonomicName>
and related species of reduced size, reaching a total length of nearly 110 mm (Eigenmann, 1912). This genus is further characterized by the wide mouth (gape same of the head width), short barbels (occasionally reaching pectoral-fin origin), small eyes without free orbital margin, absence of axillary pore, a dark saddle straddling supraoccipital area to the end of dorsal-fin base, pre-maxillary dental plate with rounded margin and thin mesocoracoid arch (Shibatta, 2003a; 2003b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3BFCA29E868A3F422100319F7C1F78CF" pageNumber="32">
Fourteen species are valid in the genus, occurring from trans-Andean drainages in Peru and Ecuador, eastward to the Orinoco and Amazon basins and southward to the 
<normalizedToken id="C338CC01D54FCFC6FE9FFD6209BCBAB1" originalValue="río">rio</normalizedToken>
de la Plata basin, Argentina (Bertaco &amp; Cardoso, 2005; Shibatta &amp; Benine, 2005). 
<taxonomicName id="52A94835EFBB903FECFC88596AAAA2DF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CF263E47-E7D3-4AE5-9772-5A3D28FE0624" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis Eigenmann 1912:130, 155" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microglanis</taxonomicName>
is also present in the eastern coastal rivers of Brazil, with the following species: 
<taxonomicName id="1F06CD04FACD12CD370951D4DE905A95" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:88D1CBA0-B876-4F2E-AA0D-8B235C0E8FA1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis cibelae Malabarba &amp; Mahler 1998:249" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cibelae">M. cibelae Malabarba &amp; Mahler-Jr., 1998</taxonomicName>
(rio 
<normalizedToken id="755E9935F901584F5F110C727DBBDC17" originalValue="Maquiné">Maquine</normalizedToken>
basin, RS), 
<taxonomicName id="FF25F02376BF927FC005EDC694E177FE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cottoides">M. cottoides (Boulenger, 1891)</taxonomicName>
(rio 
<normalizedToken id="670BEDBA5FBFE0AA64137EEBC67485A5" originalValue="Camaquã">Camaqua</normalizedToken>
basin, RS), 
<taxonomicName id="178D93DC467BF81AE97EEEF45A704FBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parahybae">M. parahybae (Steindachner, 1880)</taxonomicName>
(rio 
<normalizedToken id="0C583220A6A4E9158EB9284465B58E0B" originalValue="Paraíba">Paraiba</normalizedToken>
do Sul basin, RJ) and 
<taxonomicName id="EF5C8900EB9A718CBECC29CAB1DCFD3A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7531B5BB-D0FD-4DDB-A0F6-3589B418CED5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis nigripinnis Bizerril &amp; Perez-Neto 1992:97" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigripinnis">M. nigripinnis Bizerril &amp; Perez-Neto, 1992</taxonomicName>
(rio Macacu basin, RJ) (Bizerril &amp; Perez-Neto, 1992; Malabarba &amp; Mahler-Jr., 1998; Shibatta, 2003a).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FABA496343E48E65B6F3651E8E96E5E4" pageNumber="32">
Samples of 
<taxonomicName id="5861D18F8AB13C721E8B2287F590A3B2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CF263E47-E7D3-4AE5-9772-5A3D28FE0624" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis Eigenmann 1912:130, 155" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microglanis</taxonomicName>
were recently collected in the rio 
<normalizedToken id="F8824881D05E9A01AA3C2BDFA9D47DA5" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco basin. This is an independent hydrographic basin and has an area of 634 km2 (Cunha, 1998), across the Brazilian States of Minas Gerais, Bahia, Pernambuco, Sergipe and Alagoas. The peculiar geomorphologic aspects and the occurrence of endemic species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="17B578A04AFDDA1C23693F613BB76082" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Conorhynchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conirostris">Conorhynchus conirostris (Valenciennes, 1840)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EDF30ADFB7DCBA626CE90B531A434C60" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Duopalatinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="emarginatus">Duopalatinus emarginatus (Valenciennes, 1840)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="3F47033E77196C8D5DF8B3A01B2D8661" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Franciscodoras" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marmoratus">Franciscodoras marmoratus (Reinhardt, 1874)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C74E9FAAEA3724978C7E224B2243DF83" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F89D8D67-80A4-420E-A883-CCC96245A16C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Lophiosilurus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Lophiosilurus alexandri Steindachner 1876:154 [106]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alexandri">Lophiosilurus alexandri Steindachner, 1876</taxonomicName>
, among others), suggest an old isolation of the rio 
<normalizedToken id="B871FA4CDEB0BC825F83A3CAD170A1A5" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco system. Examination of specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="C7EB10350D941EC802FF90446A30F39D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CF263E47-E7D3-4AE5-9772-5A3D28FE0624" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microglanis Eigenmann 1912:130, 155" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microglanis</taxonomicName>
from this basin reveals that they constitute a new species, with a set of distinctive morphological characters. This new species is described herein.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
